https://pytorch.org/Get Started/Start Lo.element_content:
Select your preferences and run the install command. Stable represents the most currently tested and supported version of PyTorch. This should be suitable for many users. Preview is available if you want the latest, not fully tested and supported, builds that are generated nightly. Please ensure that you have met the prerequisites below (e.g., numpy), depending on your package manager. You can also install previous versions of PyTorch. Note that LibTorch is only available for C++.

https://pytorch.org/Get Started/Building.element_content: For the majority of PyTorch users, installing from a pre-built binary via a package manager will provide the best experience. However, there are times when you may want to install the bleeding edge PyTorch code, whether for testing or actual development on the PyTorch core. To install the latest PyTorch code, you will need to build PyTorch from source.

https://pytorch.org/Get Started/With CUD.element_content:
To install PyTorch via pip, and do have a CUDA-capable system, in the above selector, choose OS: Windows, Package: Pip and the CUDA version suited to your machine. Often, the latest CUDA version is better.

https://pytorch.org/TorchAO Quantized Mo.element_content: So far, we have released the following quantized variants of Phi4-mini-instruct, Qwen3, SmolLM3-3B, and gemma-3-270m-it: Each model mentioned has reproducible quantization recipes using the TorchAO library in its model card. This means you can use TorchAO to quantize other models as well.

https://pytorch.org/TorchAO Quantized Mo.element_content: PyTorch native quantized models benefit from strong integrations across the PyTorch ecosystem, enabling robust, high-performance quantization solutions that meet diverse deployment needs. Here is what we are using across the stack to quantize, finetune, evaluate model quality, latency and deploy the model. The released quantized models and quantization recipes work seamlessly throughout the lifecycle of model preparation and deployment.

https://pytorch.org/TorchAO Quantized Mo.element_content: PyTorch now offers native quantized variants of Phi4-mini-instruct, Qwen3, SmolLM3-3B and gemma-3-270m-it through a collaboration between the TorchAO team, ExecuTorch team, and Unsloth! These models leverage int4 and float8 quantization to deliver efficient inference on A100, H100, and mobile devices, all while maintaining minimal to no degradation in model quality compared to their bfloat16 counterparts. Highlights:

You can also reach out to us in our Discord channel. We’d also love to learn how the community quantizes models today and partner on releasing quantized models on HuggingFace in the future.

https://pytorch.org/Experience in Reduci.element_text: Experience in Reducing PT2 Compilation Time for Meta Internal Workloads
https://pytorch.org/Experience in Reduci.element_content: By Mingming Ding, James Wu, Oguz Ulgen, Sam Larsen, Bob Ren, Laith Sakka, Pian Pawakapan, Animesh Jain, Edward Yang, Yuzhen Huang, Ruilin Chen, Daohang Shi, Shuai Yang, Menglu Yu, Chunzhi Yang, Jade NieSeptember 18, 2025

https://pytorch.org/Experience in Reduci.semantic_path: https://pytorch.org/Experience in Reducing PT2 Compilation Time for Meta Internal Workloads/The Challenge of PyTorch 2.0 Compilation
https://pytorch.org/Experience in Reduci.parent_semantic_path: https://pytorch.org/Experience in Reducing PT2 Compilation Time for Meta Internal Workloads
https://pytorch.org/Experience in Reduci.element_content: Since the release of PyTorch 2.0 (PT2) and its powerful new compilation infrastructure, researchers and engineers have benefited from dramatic improvements in model execution speed and runtime efficiency. However, these gains come at a cost: initial compilation can become a significant bottleneck, especially for large and complex models like the ones used internally at Meta for recommendation.

https://pytorch.org/Experience in Reduci.semantic_path: https://pytorch.org/Experience in Reducing PT2 Compilation Time for Meta Internal Workloads/Understanding Compilation Bottlenecks
https://pytorch.org/Experience in Reduci.parent_semantic_path: https://pytorch.org/Experience in Reducing PT2 Compilation Time for Meta Internal Workloads
https://pytorch.org/Experience in Reduci.element_content: PT2 introduces a compilation step that transforms Python model code into high-performance machine code before execution. While the result is faster training and inference, compiling very large models can take up to an hour—or more—especially on cold starts, for some of our internal recommendation models with complex model architectures beyond Transformers. Figure 1. Training Overview In late 2024, we undertook a focused initiative to break down and reduce PT2 compilation time for one of our larg

https://pytorch.org/Experience in Reduci.semantic_path: https://pytorch.org/Experience in Reducing PT2 Compilation Time for Meta Internal Workloads/Tlparse
https://pytorch.org/Experience in Reduci.parent_semantic_path: https://pytorch.org/Experience in Reducing PT2 Compilation Time for Meta Internal Workloads
https://pytorch.org/Experience in Reduci.element_content: Tlparse parses structured torch trace logs and outputs HTML files analyzing data. This allows us to identify bottlenecks in various stages of compilation. Run PyTorch with the TORCH_TRACE environment variable set: Feed input into tlparse:

https://pytorch.org/Experience in Reduci.semantic_path: https://pytorch.org/Experience in Reducing PT2 Compilation Time for Meta Internal Workloads/Technique Deep-Dives
https://pytorch.org/Experience in Reduci.parent_semantic_path: https://pytorch.org/Experience in Reducing PT2 Compilation Time for Meta Internal Workloads
https://pytorch.org/Experience in Reduci.element_content: Over the past year, we have collaborated with multiple teams across Meta to develop and implement several new technologies aiming at reducing PT2 compilation time. Below is an overview of the key technologies applied to our foundation model.

https://pytorch.org/Experience in Reduci.semantic_path: https://pytorch.org/Experience in Reducing PT2 Compilation Time for Meta Internal Workloads/1. Maximize Parallelism With Triton Compilation
https://pytorch.org/Experience in Reduci.parent_semantic_path: https://pytorch.org/Experience in Reducing PT2 Compilation Time for Meta Internal Workloads
https://pytorch.org/Experience in Reduci.element_content: This optimization includes two key improvements: avoiding Triton compilation in the parent process and starting Triton compilation earlier by calling Triton in worker processes with the future cache to increase the parallelism of compilation processes. Specifically, our parallel compile workers now compile Triton kernels and pass the compiled results directly to the parent process, eliminating the need for redundant compilation in the parent. This enhances parallelism and reduces overall compile

https://pytorch.org/Experience in Reduci.semantic_path: https://pytorch.org/Experience in Reducing PT2 Compilation Time for Meta Internal Workloads/2. Dynamic Shape Marking
https://pytorch.org/Experience in Reduci.parent_semantic_path: https://pytorch.org/Experience in Reducing PT2 Compilation Time for Meta Internal Workloads
https://pytorch.org/Experience in Reduci.element_content: The use of the mark_dynamic API from PyTorch aids in identifying dynamic shapes before compilation.  Since many recompilations occur due to changes in tensor shapes during compilation, marking these shapes as dynamic can significantly reduce the number of recompilations. This, in turn, improves the overall PT2 compilation time. This process involves marking tensors as dynamic and handling specializations individually. Initially, it was challenging to determine the specializations and the best wa

https://pytorch.org/Experience in Reduci.semantic_path: https://pytorch.org/Experience in Reducing PT2 Compilation Time for Meta Internal Workloads/3. Autotuning Configuration Pruning
https://pytorch.org/Experience in Reduci.parent_semantic_path: https://pytorch.org/Experience in Reducing PT2 Compilation Time for Meta Internal Workloads
https://pytorch.org/Experience in Reduci.element_content: We found that the number of user kernels and user-defined configurations applied to the foundation model significantly impacts PT2 compilation Because PT2 autotuning automatically benchmarks many possible runtime configurations for each kernel to find the most efficient one, which can be very time-consuming when there are many kernels and configurations. To address this, we developed a process to identify the most time-consuming kernels and determine optimal runtime configurations for implementa

https://pytorch.org/Experience in Reduci.semantic_path: https://pytorch.org/Experience in Reducing PT2 Compilation Time for Meta Internal Workloads/4. Improve Caching Hit Rates
https://pytorch.org/Experience in Reduci.parent_semantic_path: https://pytorch.org/Experience in Reducing PT2 Compilation Time for Meta Internal Workloads
https://pytorch.org/Experience in Reduci.element_content: Profile-guided optimization(PGO) can disrupt caching, leading to non-deterministic cache keys, which cause cache misses and result in long compilation time.

https://pytorch.org/Experience in Reduci.semantic_path: https://pytorch.org/Experience in Reducing PT2 Compilation Time for Meta Internal Workloads/5. Optimize Kernel Launching
https://pytorch.org/Experience in Reduci.parent_semantic_path: https://pytorch.org/Experience in Reducing PT2 Compilation Time for Meta Internal Workloads
https://pytorch.org/Experience in Reduci.element_content: Regular Triton kernels have a high launch cost due to needing to codegen C++ at compile time, and have low cache hit rates on ads models. The StaticCudaLauncher is a new PyTorch launcher for Triton-generated CUDA kernels, which we used as the default launcher for all Triton kernels. This led to faster compile times on both cold and warm start.

https://pytorch.org/Experience in Reduci.semantic_path: https://pytorch.org/Experience in Reducing PT2 Compilation Time for Meta Internal Workloads/6. Mega-Caching
https://pytorch.org/Experience in Reduci.parent_semantic_path: https://pytorch.org/Experience in Reducing PT2 Compilation Time for Meta Internal Workloads
https://pytorch.org/Experience in Reduci.element_content: MegaCache brings together several types of PT2 compilation caches—including components like inductor (the core PT2 compiler), triton bundler (for GPU code), AOT Autograd (for efficient gradient computation), Dynamo PGO (profile-guided optimizations), and autotune settings—into a single archive that can be easily downloaded and shared. By consolidating these elements, MegaCache offers those improvements: Mega-Cache provides two compiler APIs:

https://pytorch.org/Experience in Reduci.semantic_path: https://pytorch.org/Experience in Reducing PT2 Compilation Time for Meta Internal Workloads/Results and Impact 80 Faster Compilation
https://pytorch.org/Experience in Reduci.parent_semantic_path: https://pytorch.org/Experience in Reducing PT2 Compilation Time for Meta Internal Workloads
https://pytorch.org/Experience in Reduci.element_content: Thanks to our optimization efforts, the compilation time for one of our largest foundation models during offline training has been reduced by more than 80%, decreasing from around 3000 seconds to just under 500 seconds over the past year. Figure 4. PT2 Compilation Time Trend

https://pytorch.org/Experience in Reduci.semantic_path: https://pytorch.org/Experience in Reducing PT2 Compilation Time for Meta Internal Workloads/In the End
https://pytorch.org/Experience in Reduci.parent_semantic_path: https://pytorch.org/Experience in Reducing PT2 Compilation Time for Meta Internal Workloads
https://pytorch.org/Experience in Reduci.element_content: We have integrated these optimizations into the PT2 compiler stack, making them the default for all users compiling models with PT2. Our generalized transformation approach is designed to benefit a wide range of models beyond Meta’s ecosystem, and we welcome ongoing discussions and improvements inspired by this work.

https://pytorch.org/Experience in Reduci.element_content: Many thanks to Max Leung, Musharaf Sultan, John Bocharov, and Gregory Chanan for their insightful support and reviews.

https://pytorch.org/Join PyTorch Foundat.element_content: If your organization is interested in becoming a Member of the PyTorch Foundation, please complete the Member Enrollment form and designate someone with signature authority for your institution for the membership approval process. For Premier Membership you must also complete the Premier Membership Questionnaire after submitting your membership application. The Foundation will review your application after both have been submitted. Please note, membership is not required to participate in PyTorc

https://pytorch.org/Join the PyTorch Eco.element_content: Applying to join the PyTorch Ecosystem is simple: Once submitted, your application enters the review pipeline managed by the PyTorch Ecosystem Working Group.

All applications are tracked via the PyTorch Ecosystem Project Board. Applications are reviewed on a first-come, first-served basis. The Working Group reviews approximately 7–10 projects per session, depending on availability. Projects are moved to “In Progress” roughly two weeks before a scheduled review session. elements.sibling_content: So far, we have released the following quantized variants of Phi4-mini-instruct, Qwen3, SmolLM3-3B, and gemma-3-270m-it:
paragraphs: PyTorch now offers native quantized variants of Phi4-mini-instruct, Qwen3, SmolLM3-3B and gemma-3-270m-it through a collaboration between the TorchAO team, ExecuTorch team, and Unsloth! These models leverage int4 and float8 quantization to deliver efficient inference on A100, H100, and mobile devices, all while maintaining minimal to no degradation in model quality compared to their bfloat16 counterparts. elements.sibling_content: Since the release of PyTorch 2.0 (PT2) and its powerful new compilation infrastructure, researchers and engineers have benefited from dramatic improvements in model execution speed and runtime efficiency. However, these gains come at a cost: initial compilation can become a significant bottleneck, especially for large and complex models like the ones used internally at Meta for recommendation.
paragraphs: Since the release of PyTorch 2.0 (PT2) and its powerful new compilation infrastructure, researchers and engineers have benefited from dramatic improvements in model execution speed and runtime efficiency. However, these gains come at a cost: initial compilation can become a significant bottleneck, especially for large and complex models like the ones used internally at Meta for recommendation.
PT2 introduces a compilation step that transforms Python model code into high-performance machine code before execution.

While the result is faster training and inference, compiling very large models can take up to an hour—or more—especially on cold starts, for some of our internal recommendation models with complex model architectures beyond Transformers.

heading_to_content.The Challenge of PyTorch 2.0 Compilation: Since the release of PyTorch 2.0 (PT2) and its powerful new compilation infrastructure, researchers and engineers have benefited from dramatic improvements in model execution speed and runtime efficiency. However, these gains come at a cost: initial compilation can become a significant bottleneck, especially for large and complex models like the ones used internally at Meta for recommendation.

heading.text: Experience in Reducing PT2 Compilation Time for Meta Internal Workloads

paragraphs: If your organization is interested in becoming a Member of the PyTorch Foundation, please complete the Member Enrollment form and designate someone with signature authority for your institution for the membership approval process.

For Premier Membership you must also complete the Premier Membership Questionnaire after submitting your membership application. The Foundation will review your application after both have been submitted.
Please note, membership is not required to participate in PyTorch as an individual contributor. You can join the community at any time and collaborate with others interested in the project.

element_relationships.Join PyTorch Foundation: As a member of the PyTorch Foundation, you’ll have access to resources that allow you to be stewards of stable, secure, and long-lasting codebases. You can collaborate on training, local and regional events, open-source developer tooling, academic research, and guides to help new users and contributors have a productive experience.
element_relationships.Key Features & Capabilities:
PRODUCTION READY

Transition seamlessly between eager and graph modes with TorchScript, and accelerate the path to production with TorchServe.

DISTRIBUTED TRAINING

Scalable distributed training and performance optimization in research and production is enabled by the torch.distributed backend.

ROBUST ECOSYSTEM

A rich ecosystem of tools and libraries extends PyTorch and supports development in computer vision, NLP and more.

CLOUD SUPPORT

PyTorch is well supported on major cloud platforms, providing frictionless development and easy scaling.

element_relationships.Install PyTorch: Select your preferences and run the install command. Stable represents the most currently tested and supported version of PyTorch. This should be suitable for many users. Preview is available if you want the latest, not fully tested and supported, builds that are generated nightly. Please ensure that you have met the prerequisites below (e.g., numpy), depending on your package manager. Anaconda is our recommended package manager since it installs all dependencies. You can also install previous versions of PyTorch. Note that LibTorch is only available for C++.

element_relationships.Start Locally:
Select your preferences and run the install command. Stable represents the most currently tested and supported version of PyTorch. This should be suitable for many users. Preview is available if you want the latest, not fully tested and supported, builds that are generated nightly. Please ensure that you have met the prerequisites below (e.g., numpy), depending on your package manager. You can also install previous versions of PyTorch. Note that LibTorch is only available for C++.

NOTE: Latest Stable PyTorch requires Python 3.9 or later. Latest Preview (Nightly) PyTorch requires Python 3.10 or later.

element_relationships.The Challenge of PyTorch 2.0 Compilation: Since the release of PyTorch 2.0 (PT2) and its powerful new compilation infrastructure, researchers and engineers have benefited from dramatic improvements in model execution speed and runtime efficiency. However, these gains come at a cost: initial compilation can become a significant bottleneck, especially for large and complex models like the ones used internally at Meta for recommendation.

element_relationships.PyTorch documentation: PyTorch is an optimized tensor library for deep learning using GPUs and CPUs.
element_relationships.Learn the Basics: Created On: Feb 09, 2021 | Last Updated: Jul 07, 2025 | Last Verified: Nov 05, 2024
element_relationships.Introduction to PyTorch on YouTube: An introduction to building a complete ML workflow with PyTorch. Follows the PyTorch Beginner Series on YouTube.
element_relationships.Learning PyTorch with Examples: This tutorial introduces the fundamental concepts of PyTorch through self-contained examples.
element_relationships.What is torch.nn really?: Use torch.nn to create and train a neural network.
element_relationships.Visualizing Models, Data, and Training w: Learn to use TensorBoard to visualize data and model training.
element_relationships.Good usage of `non_blocking` and `pin_me: A guide on best practices to copy data from CPU to GPU.
element_relationships.Understanding requires_grad, retain_grad: Learn the subtleties of requires_grad, retain_grad, leaf, and non-leaf tensors
element_relationships.Visualizing Gradients in PyTorch: Visualize the gradient flow of a network.
element_relationships.TorchVision Object Detection Finetuning: Finetune a pre-trained Mask R-CNN model.
element_relationships.Transfer Learning for Computer Vision Tu: Train a convolutional neural network for image classification using transfer learning.
element_relationships.Adversarial Example Generation: Train a convolutional neural network for image classification using transfer learning.
element_relationships.DCGAN Tutorial: Train a generative adversarial network (GAN) to generate new celebrities.
element_relationships.Spatial Transformer Networks Tutorial: Learn how to augment your network using a visual attention mechanism.
element_relationships.Semi-Supervised Learning Tutorial Based: Learn how to train semi-supervised learning algorithms (on custom data) using USB and PyTorch.
element_relationships.Audio IO: Learn to load data with torchaudio.
element_relationships.Audio Resampling: Learn to resample audio waveforms using torchaudio.
element_relationships.Audio Data Augmentation: Learn to apply data augmentations using torchaudio.
element_relationships.Audio Feature Extractions: Learn to extract features using torchaudio.
element_relationships.Audio Feature Augmentation: Learn to augment features using torchaudio.
element_relationships.Automatic Speech Recognition with Wav2Ve: Learn how to use torchaudio's pretrained models for building a speech recognition application.
element_relationships.Speech Command Classification: Learn how to correctly format an audio dataset and then train/test an audio classifier network on the dataset.
element_relationships.Text-to-Speech with torchaudio: Learn how to use torchaudio's pretrained models for building a text-to-speech application.
element_relationships.Forced Alignment with Wav2Vec2 in torcha: Learn how to use torchaudio's Wav2Vec2 pretrained models for aligning text to speech
element_relationships.NLP from Scratch: Classifying Names with: Build and train a basic character-level RNN to classify word from scratch without the use of torchtext. First in a series of three tutorials.
element_relationships.NLP from Scratch: Generating Names with: After using character-level RNN to classify names, learn how to generate names from languages. Second in a series of three tutorials.
element_relationships.NLP from Scratch: Translation with a Seq: This is the third and final tutorial on doing “NLP From Scratch”, where we write our own classes and functions to preprocess the data to do our NLP modeling tasks.
element_relationships.Exporting a PyTorch model to ONNX using: Build a image classifier model in PyTorch and convert it to ONNX before deploying it with ONNX Runtime.
element_relationships.Extending the ONNX exporter operator sup: Demonstrate end-to-end how to address unsupported operators in ONNX.
element_relationships.Exporting a model with control flow to O: Demonstrate how to handle control flow logic while exporting a PyTorch model to ONNX.
element_relationships.Reinforcement Learning (DQN): Learn how to use PyTorch to train a Deep Q Learning (DQN) agent on the CartPole-v0 task from the OpenAI Gym.
element_relationships.Reinforcement Learning (PPO) with TorchR: Learn how to use PyTorch and TorchRL to train a Proximal Policy Optimization agent on the Inverted Pendulum task from Gym.
element_relationships.Train a Mario-playing RL Agent: Use PyTorch to train a Double Q-learning agent to play Mario.
element_relationships.Recurrent DQN: Use TorchRL to train recurrent policies
element_relationships.Code a DDPG Loss: Use TorchRL to code a DDPG Loss
element_relationships.Writing your environment and transforms: Use TorchRL to code a Pendulum
element_relationships.Profiling PyTorch: Learn how to profile a PyTorch application
element_relationships.Building a Simple Performance Profiler w: Build a simple FX interpreter to record the runtime of op, module, and function calls and report statistics
element_relationships.(beta) Channels Last Memory Format in Py: Get an overview of Channels Last memory format and understand how it is used to order NCHW tensors in memory preserving dimensions.
element_relationships.Using the PyTorch C++ Frontend: Walk through an end-to-end example of training a model with the C++ frontend by training a DCGAN – a kind of generative model – to generate images of MNIST digits.
element_relationships.PyTorch Custom Operators Landing Page: This is the landing page for all things related to custom operators in PyTorch.
element_relationships.Custom Python Operators: Create Custom Operators in Python. Useful for black-boxing a Python function for use with torch.compile.
element_relationships.Compiled Autograd: Capturing a larger ba: Learn how to use compiled autograd to capture a larger backward graph.
element_relationships.Custom C++ and CUDA Operators: How to extend PyTorch with custom C++ and CUDA operators.
element_relationships.Autograd in C++ Frontend: The autograd package helps build flexible and dynamic neural netorks. In this tutorial, explore several examples of doing autograd in PyTorch C++ frontend
element_relationships.Registering a Dispatched Operator in C++: The dispatcher is an internal component of PyTorch which is responsible for figuring out what code should actually get run when you call a function like torch::add.
element_relationships.Extending Dispatcher For a New Backend i: Learn how to extend the dispatcher to add a new device living outside of the pytorch/pytorch repo and maintain it to keep in sync with native PyTorch devices.
element_relationships.Facilitating New Backend Integration by: Learn how to integrate a new backend living outside of the pytorch/pytorch repo and maintain it to keep in sync with the native PyTorch backend.
element_relationships.Custom Function Tutorial: Double Backwar: Learn how to write a custom autograd Function that supports double backward.
element_relationships.Custom Function Tutorial: Fusing Convolu: Learn how to create a custom autograd Function that fuses batch norm into a convolution to improve memory usage.
element_relationships.Forward-mode Automatic Differentiation: Learn how to use forward-mode automatic differentiation.
element_relationships.Jacobians, Hessians, hvp, vhp, and more: Learn how to compute advanced autodiff quantities using torch.func
element_relationships.Model Ensembling: Learn how to ensemble models using torch.vmap
element_relationships.Per-Sample-Gradients: Learn how to compute per-sample-gradients using torch.func
element_relationships.Neural Tangent Kernels: Learn how to compute neural tangent kernels using torch.func
element_relationships.Performance Profiling in PyTorch: Learn how to use the PyTorch Profiler to benchmark your module's performance.
element_relationships.Performance Profiling in TensorBoard: Learn how to use the TensorBoard plugin to profile and analyze your model's performance.
element_relationships.Hyperparameter Tuning Tutorial: Learn how to use Ray Tune to find the best performing set of hyperparameters for your model.
element_relationships.Parametrizations Tutorial: Learn how to use torch.nn.utils.parametrize to put constraints on your parameters (e.g. make them orthogonal, symmetric positive definite, low-rank...)
element_relationships.Pruning Tutorial: Learn how to use torch.nn.utils.prune to sparsify your neural networks, and how to extend it to implement your own custom pruning technique.
element_relationships.How to save memory by fusing the optimiz: Learn a memory-saving technique through fusing the optimizer step into the backward pass using memory snapshots.
element_relationships.(beta) Accelerating BERT with semi-struc: Train BERT, prune it to be 2:4 sparse, and then accelerate it to achieve 2x inference speedups with semi-structured sparsity and torch.compile.
element_relationships.Multi-Objective Neural Architecture Sear: Learn how to use Ax to search over architectures find optimal tradeoffs between accuracy and latency.
element_relationships.torch.compile Tutorial: Speed up your models with minimal code changes using torch.compile, the latest PyTorch compiler solution.
element_relationships.Building a Convolution/Batch Norm fuser: Build a simple pattern matcher pass that fuses batch norm into convolution to improve performance during inference.
element_relationships.Inductor CPU Backend Debugging and Profi: Learn the usage, debugging and performance profiling for ``torch.compile`` with Inductor CPU backend.
element_relationships.(beta) Implementing High-Performance Tra: This tutorial explores the new torch.nn.functional.scaled_dot_product_attention and how it can be used to construct Transformer components.
element_relationships.Knowledge Distillation in Convolutional: Learn how to improve the accuracy of lightweight models using more powerful models as teachers.
element_relationships.Accelerating PyTorch Transformers by rep: This tutorial goes over recommended best practices for implementing Transformers with native PyTorch.
element_relationships.PyTorch Distributed Overview: Briefly go over all concepts and features in the distributed package. Use this document to find the distributed training technology that can best serve your application.
element_relationships.Distributed Data Parallel in PyTorch - V: This series of video tutorials walks you through distributed training in PyTorch via DDP.
element_relationships.Single-Machine Model Parallel Best Pract: Learn how to implement model parallel, a distributed training technique which splits a single model onto different GPUs, rather than replicating the entire model on each GPU
element_relationships.Getting Started with Distributed Data Pa: Learn the basics of when to use distributed data paralle versus data parallel and work through an example to set it up.
element_relationships.Writing Distributed Applications with Py: Set up the distributed package of PyTorch, use the different communication strategies, and go over some the internals of the package.
element_relationships.Large Scale Transformer model training w: Learn how to train large models with Tensor Parallel package.
element_relationships.Customize Process Group Backends Using C: Extend ProcessGroup with custom collective communication implementations.
element_relationships.Getting Started with Distributed RPC Fra: Learn how to build distributed training using the torch.distributed.rpc package.
element_relationships.Implementing a Parameter Server Using Di: Walk through a through a simple example of implementing a parameter server using PyTorch’s Distributed RPC framework.
element_relationships.Introduction to Distributed Pipeline Par: Demonstrate how to implement pipeline parallelism using torch.distributed.pipelining
element_relationships.Implementing Batch RPC Processing Using: Learn how to use rpc.functions.async_execution to implement batch RPC
element_relationships.Combining Distributed DataParallel with: Walk through a through a simple example of how to combine distributed data parallelism with distributed model parallelism.
element_relationships.Getting Started with Fully Sharded Data: Learn how to train models with Fully Sharded Data Parallel (fully_shard) package.
element_relationships.Introduction to Libuv TCPStore Backend: TCPStore now uses a new server backend for faster connection and better scalability.
element_relationships.Exporting to ExecuTorch Tutorial: Learn about how to use ExecuTorch, a unified ML stack for lowering PyTorch models to edge devices.
element_relationships.Running an ExecuTorch Model in C++ Tutor: Learn how to load and execute an ExecuTorch model in C++
element_relationships.Using the ExecuTorch SDK to Profile a Mo: Explore how to use the ExecuTorch SDK to profile, debug, and visualize ExecuTorch models
element_relationships.Building an ExecuTorch iOS Demo App: Explore how to set up the ExecuTorch iOS Demo App, which uses the MobileNet v3 model to process live camera images leveraging three different backends: XNNPACK, Core ML, and Metal Performance Shaders (MPS).
element_relationships.Building an ExecuTorch Android Demo App: Learn how to set up the ExecuTorch Android Demo App for image segmentation tasks using the DeepLab v3 model and XNNPACK FP32 backend.
element_relationships.Lowering a Model as a Delegate: Learn to accelerate your program using ExecuTorch by applying delegates through three methods: lowering the whole module, composing it with another module, and partitioning parts of a module.
element_relationships.Introduction to TorchRec: TorchRec is a PyTorch domain library built to provide common sparsity & parallelism primitives needed for large-scale recommender systems.
element_relationships.Exploring TorchRec sharding: This tutorial covers the sharding schemes of embedding tables by using EmbeddingPlanner and DistributedModelParallel API.
